The paper deals with learning continuous probabilistic graphical models in the face of missing data, which is a common problem in machine learning. The Copula Bayesian Network (CBN) density model is introduced as a flexible framework that captures complex high-dimensional dependency structures while offering direct control over the univariate marginals, leading to improved generalization. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

The paper also discusses the computational advantages of the CBN model when training data is partially observed, and derives a computationally amenable learning objective that is a lower bound on the log-likelihood function. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) and Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper demonstrates the effectiveness of the approach for learning the structure and parameters of a CBN model for two real-life continuous domains, which suggests that it may also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
